context: The Company's headquarters in <a0_0><b5_0>London<b5_0/><a0_0/>, from which much of India was governed, was <a1_0><b6_0>East India House<b6_0/><a1_0/> in Leadenhall Street. After occupying premises in Philpot Lane from 1600 to 1621; in Crosby House, Bishopsgate, from 1621 to 1638; and in <a2_0><b7_0>Leadenhall Street<b7_0/><a2_0/> from 1638 to 1648, the Company moved into <a3_0><b8_0>Craven House<b8_0/><a3_0/>, an Elizabethan mansion in Leadenhall Street. The building had become known as East India House by 1661. It was completely rebuilt and enlarged in 1726–9; and further significantly remodelled and expanded in 1796–1800. It was finally vacated in 1860 and demolished in 1861–62. The site is now occupied by <a4_0><b9_0>the Lloyd's building<b9_0/><a4_0/>.
